node.text:
🔊 All last week, we shared content with you from the Coral Triangle — and now, we want to invite you to come behind-the-scenes of our conservation journey in Timor-Leste, a young nation whose enchanting waters are bursting with an incredible variety of life, where they are making responsible and sustainable ecotourism an ideal way for local communities to support themselves. 

Join @mitty, @paulnicklen, and @andy_mann in the rich marine ecosystem of Timor-Leste for an unforgettable encounter with the goliath of the ocean: the blue whale. 

Shot by @paulnicklen, @mitty, and @andy_mann on @sonyalpha.

#ShotOnSony #BeAlpha #SonyAlpha

node.title: Behind the Scenes: SeaLegacy’s Conservation Journey | Timor-Leste

node.text:
In the final episode of our 'The Bahamas 2019' series, the team spends some time with the locals — Bahamians whose lives and culture revolve around and are dependent on their relationship with the ocean. Yet, the marine ecosystems in The Bahamas remain under constant threat of increased pollution, coastal development, unsustainable fishing practices, and the ever compounding effects of climate change. 

Our team's unforgettable experiences in The Bahamas in the past continue to fuel our dedication to advocating and fighting for the ecosystem and communities here in the present.

⛵ Can't get enough behind-the-scenes action? Well, you're in luck — starting next week, tune in to our stories to see what it's like to be part of the crew aboard The #SeaLegacy1 as we continue to support the needs of Bahamians on the ground over the coming months. #TurningTheTide

***The footage from this series was captured on expedition in early 2019, in a pre-COVID and pre-Dorian world

@paulnicklen @mitty @andy_mann @samkretch @moorecharitable @trevor_bacon1 @ceibahamas

#OnlyOneOcean #Bahamas

“We have a 97% failure rate. People think we just show up and know exactly where the animals are… and that’s not how it is.” - @paulnicklen 

On today's behind-the-scenes blast from the past, @paulnicklen, @mitty, @andy_mann, and the team embark on a true on-the-ground exploratory expedition in The Bahamas where they make some disheartening discoveries on a remote reef. 

Part of our job as storytellers is documenting both the beauty and the threats facing our ocean. This type of exploration comes with both victories and struggles, but no matter what we find, there are lessons to be learned and work we can do to keep #TurningTheTide.

We want to take you back in time to an unforgettable SeaLegacy expedition to The Bahamas — a past journey that has inspired our dedication to this incredible country and its invaluable ecosystems. The experiences our team had in 2019 are part of the reason the #SeaLegacy1 crew is on the ground there now!

Starting today, we will be sharing our 'The Bahamas 2019: Behind-the-Scenes' series with you. These never-before-seen SeaLegacy Diaries feature white-tip shark encounters with @andy_mann, blue hole filming challenges with @paulnicklen, endangered coral reef discoveries with @mitty, and more. Stay tuned all week — you won't want to miss any of it! 

***The footage from this series was captured on expedition in early 2019, in a pre-COVID and pre-Dorian world

Despite pledges by the Ecuadorian government to protect Galápagos, a World Heritage Site and refuge for 3,000 marine species, industrial and unsustainable fishing practices are plundering its waters, devastating this delicate ecosystem. 

We’re calling on Ecuadorian President Lenín Moreno @leninmorenog and President of the National Assembly @cesarlitardo to fulfill their commitment to protect Galápagos and urgently expand the Galápagos Marine Reserve. Please show your support by signing the petition at only.one/galapagos (link in our story) and share!

#masgalapagos #yoestoycongalapagos #galapagos #ecuador

A pesar de las promesas del gobierno ecuatoriano de proteger Galápagos, Patrimonio Mundial y refugio de 3,000 especies marinas, la pesca industrial e insostenible está saqueando sus aguas, devastando este delicado ecosistema. 

Hacemos un llamado al presidente ecuatoriano Lenín Moreno @leninmorenog y al presidente de la Asamblea Nacional @cesarlitardo para que cumplan su promesa de proteger Galápagos y amplíen la Reserva Marina de Galápagos. Muestra tu apoyo firmando la petición en only.one/galapagos (link en story) ¡y por favor comparte!
.
.
.

Special thanks to @dvfernandez and @luksth for narrating and @robertoochoahe for contributing footage to this video. 
.
.
@mission_blue @migramarnet @mas_galapagos2020

URGENT! We need your help! The Bahamian government has granted a license for offshore oil drilling that could start as soon as December 2020.

This project risks devastating the way of life for this ocean nation. Just one accident, one spill, would have dire consequences for both marine systems in the region and for Bahamians who depend on the ocean for their economy, employment, food sources, recreation, and culture. 

Young Bahamian leaders are urging their Prime Minister,  @opmthebahamas, to stop the project, and they need our help. 

“We refuse to stand by while our islands are endangered. We are not an oil nation. We are an ocean nation. It’s our past, our present, and our future."

Together, we can help these young leaders, @alannahvellacott, @laurenaritchie, @catislandkita, and @natureboyniel, Stop Oil Drilling in the #Bahamas.

Head to our story for the link to sign @OnlyOne's petition and learn more at only.one/bahamas

node.title: Stop Oil Drilling in the Bahamas

Threats to biodiversity are threats to all life on Earth. That includes us — human beings.

Because biodiversity IS life on Earth. 

Right now, one million plant and animal species are at risk of extinction. At @SeaLegacy, we are deeply concerned, but not defeated. 

If we can protect 30% of our lands, and 30% of our ocean by 2030 we can help reverse the loss of life around the globe. 

Please follow our friends at @ConservationOrg to stay up to date on their work.

40,000+ of you have already stood up and demanded that the government of Costa Rica put a stop to the killing of endangered sharks in it waters. Your support is critical – thank you! We will soon deliver the signed petition to President @carlosalvq, sending a strong message that current practices are unacceptable and must change. You can still sign the petition at the link in our bio.⁠
⁠
Costa Rica has more than 40 species of sharks and the fishing industry is absolutely decimating their populations. Half the species are in serious danger of extinction, and hammerhead sharks could be completely wiped out in the next 20 years if trends continue. The rapid decline of endangered sharks in Costa Rica is nothing short of shameful.⁠
⁠
Earlier this year the Costa Rican government removed the ability of the Ministry of Environment to protect sharks and shifted management responsibilities to the Institute of Fisheries and Aquaculture (INCOPESCA). The agency lacks the capacity to effectively monitor shark populations. In fact, they benefit from their commercialization.⁠
⁠
Please add your voice to the petition today at only.one/act/costarica⁠
⁠
#Costarica #sharks #endangeredspecies #petition #turningthetide

There are only a few truly wild places left on earth. We must to do everything we can to protect them. Over 60 million fish travel upriver here each year and bring life to the bear oasis that is Katmai National Park and Preserve. In its bays and streams, massive brown bears gather by the dozen along the water's edge, feasting side by side.⁠
⁠
The proposed construction of Pebble Mine will have catastrophic effects on salmon and bears of the Bristol Bay, Alaska watershed if it is not stopped. The project threatens 3,500 acres of wetlands and 80 miles of salmon streams in this part of the world. We cannot let this beautiful place turn into another industrial wasteland.⁠
⁠
Visit the link in our bio to learn more.⁠
⁠
Video by @paulnicklen⁠.⁠
⁠
#SaveBristolBay #nopebblemine #Alaska #grizzlybear

If you haven’t already signed the petition to stop the killing of sharks in Costa Rica, there’s still time. Head to the link in our bio to add your name and demand action from the government of Costa Rica.  So far, more than 38,000 people have signed. Thank you for standing up for sharks!⁠
⁠
We will soon deliver the petition to the government of Costa Rica in hopes that they will reinstall critical protections for the endangered sharks in their waters.⁠
⁠
Earlier this year, the country essentially legalized the overfishing, and subsequent extinction, of endangered sharks. President @carlosalvq removed the ability of the Ministry of Environment to protect sharks, and shifted management responsibilities to the Institute of Fisheries and Aquaculture (INCOPESCA) – meaning they are no longer protected by Costa Rica’s Wildlife Conservation Law.⁠
⁠
Please, sign the petition today at only.one/act/costarica⁠
⁠
Video by @paulnicklen ⁠
⁠
#sharks #ocean #conservation #turningthetide #petition #costarica

This month, The Tide is partnering with the Sea Turtle Conservancy in Panama (@conserveturtles, @conserveturtlesbocas) – the oldest turtle conservation organization in the world. We are supporting their work to protect four species of endangered sea turtles on an uninhabited island off the Caribbean coast within Bastimentos Island National Marine Park. These turtles are up against serious threats: clandestine fishing with harpoons and nets, direct poaching of nesting females, and accidental maiming with longlines intended to catch sharks to name a few. ⁠
⁠
For over a decade, the communities of the Ngäbe-Buglé comarca (traditional region) have been at the heart of efforts to save sea turtles in the region. More than 30 community members now work as part of the Sea Turtle Conservancy. On Chiriquí Beach alone, they take care of approximately 4,000 turtle nests each year. But it’s extremely challenging to work on an island with no electricity or running water and the organization needed help to continue with their critical mission. That’s where support from The Tide comes in! ⁠
⁠
To learn more, read the impact report on our efforts to support The Sea Turtle Conservancy at the link in our bio. Together we are standing up for endangered sea turtles, and we are making a difference! ⁠
⁠
Our community of Tide members from all over the world provides support for organizations and individuals on the frontlines of ocean conservation. We are grateful and proud to join forces with 7,400+ people to directly support the work that is protecting our oceans and safeguarding its wildlife. 

Video by @sealegacy and @onlyone ⁠
⁠
#Panama #seaturtles #turtles #oceanconservation #TurningTheTide #marineanimals #marineconservation #marinewildlife #endangeredspecies

node.text:
When the ocean’s delicate ecosystems are left in peace, undisturbed, they flourish as nature intended. Cuba’s Jardines De La Reina (Gardens of the Queen) is a shining example of a healthy, protected reef ecosystem functioning exactly as it should. As @paulnicklen elaborates, ‘it’s life, stacked upon life, stacked upon life.’⁠
⁠
One of the last remaining intact ecosystems on earth, this ecological jewel shows how strong ocean guardianship makes all the difference. Cuba protects more than 25% of its waters. The coral reefs remain as they were thousands of years ago – untouched and thriving. The number one thing that’s special about this area is how they limit the access of ships and impose strict regulations on any human activity. The management of Gardens of the Queen is a blueprint of success that can be followed by every other Caribbean nation.⁠
⁠
Watch the fascinating seven-episode video series on Gardens of the Queen at the link in our bio, and join the @SeaLegacy team on expedition as our storytellers discover the hidden lives of the crocodiles, sharks, grouper, lobster, sardines and other species that make the Gardens such a unique and spectacular place.⁠
⁠
Video by @andy_mann⁠
⁠
#Cuba #jardinesdelareina #gardensofthequeen #mangroves #coralreef #ecosystem #TurnTheTide

Spending time in the mangroves swimming alongside these beautiful animals is both a powerful and humbling experience. Drop a 🐊 in the comments if you believe all Earth's creatures deserve protection.

Cuba's Gardens of the Queen, (Jardines De La Reina), is one of the healthiest and most vibrant marine ecosystems in the world. Strictly protected since 1996, the Gardens show us what’s possible when we commit to creating healthy and abundant oceans. The area is home to untouched, intact mangrove, seagrass, and coral reef ecosystems that support an abundance of species — including the powerful but often misunderstood American crocodile.

In the Gardens, the crocs can be found trawling thick seagrass beds and sheltering themselves in clusters of thriving mangroves. These shelter-providing, nutrient-rich ecosystems are unsung climate heroes that hold the power to effectively remove carbon dioxide out of our atmosphere! 

On this  #WorldMangroveDay, we recognize that by protecting mangroves we can support coastal communities and help slow climate change.

Photos by @Mitty

#TurningTheTide #ApexPredators #Cuba #WorldMangroveDay #mangroves

“The dolphins were using their echolocation to spot single, silver fish hiding deep in the soft sand. They would dive in with their snouts, sometimes all the way down to their pectoral fins, before wriggling back out with their catch. Imagine the incredible senses they have evolved through time! I could not believe they let me within a couple of feet with my noisy scuba bubbles as if I didn’t exist.” @Paulnicklen⁠
⁠
The wildlife in our oceans is an endless source of wonder, and we are constantly inspired to do everything we can to protect it. We’re so incredibly grateful to have a dedicated community behind us investing in conservation work. We could not do it without our passionate Tide members! Thank you for standing together with us to shape a better future for our oceans. We are blown away by the support we’ve received over the past week — this level of dedication and passion for ocean conservation fills us with so much hope.⁠
⁠
Tomorrow is the last opportunity to win Paul’s Super Sea Wolf 53 Zodiac Watch – the same watch that accompanied him diving in The Bahamas capturing fascinating footage. He’s giving it away as a thank you for everything you’re doing to help. Enter at the link in our bio.⁠
⁠
Thank you, again and again!⁠
⁠
Video by @Paulnicklen⁠
⁠
#oceanconservation #climatechange #thetide #entertowin#bottlenosedolphin #bahamas #craterfeeding⁠
